===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*tend-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|attenden}}, {{m|enm|atenden}}, from {{der|en|fro|atendre||to attend, listen}}, from {{der|en|la|attendere||to stretch toward, give heed to}}, from {{m|la|ad||to}} + {{m|la|tendere||to stretch}}; see [[tend]] and compare [[attempt]].

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|archaic|transitive}} To [[listen]] to (something or someone); to pay attention to; regard; heed. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Sidney Arcadia}}
#*: The diligent pilot in a dangerous tempest doth not '''attend''' the unskilful words of the passenger.
#* {{RQ:Swift Tale of a Tub|section=IX|sectionname=A Digression Concerning the Original, the Use and Improvement of Madness in a Commonwealth|pages=169–170|pageref=170|passage=The preſent Argument is the moſt abſtracted that ever I engaged in, it ſtrains my Faculties to their higheſt Stretch; and I deſire the Reader to '''attend''' with utmoſt perpenſity; For, I now proceed to unravel this knotty Point.}}
# {{lb|en|archaic|intransitive}} To [[listen]] ({{m|en|to}}, {{m|en|unto}}). {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#* '''1912''', {{w|Rudyard Kipling}}, ''[[s:The Beginning of the Armadillos|The Beginning of the Armadillos]]''
#*: 'Now '''attend''' to me,' said Painted Jaguar, 'because this is very important. {{...}}
# {{senseid|en|to turn one's consideration to, deal with}}{{lb|en|intransitive}} To turn one's [[consideration]] ({{m|en|to}}); to [[deal]] with (a task, problem, concern etc.), to look after. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|Secretaries '''attend''' to correspondence.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1918| author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}| chapter=15| title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]| passage=Edward Churchill still '''attended''' to his work in a hopeless mechanical manner like a sleep-walker who walks safely on a well-known round. But his Roman collar galled him, his cossack stifled him, his biretta was as uncomfortable as a merry-andrew's cap and bells.}}
# {{lb|en|ambitransitive}} To [[wait upon]] as a [[servant]] etc.; to accompany to assist (someone). {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|Valets '''attend''' to their employer's wardrobe.}}
#: {{ux|en|Servants '''attend''' the king day and night.}}
#* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|book=I|canto=X|stanza=41|passage=The fift had charge sicke persons to '''attend'''}}
#*{{RQ:Shakespeare Verona|I|iii|passage=youthful Valentine<br>'''Attends''' the emperor in his royal court.}}
#* {{RQ:Macaulay History of England|chapter=13|passage=With a sore heart and a gloomy brow, he prepared to '''attend''' William thither.}}
# {{senseid|en|to be present at}}{{lb|en|transitive}} To be [[present]] at (an event or place) in order to take part in some action or proceedings; to regularly go to (an event or place). {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|Children must '''attend''' primary school.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}| title={{w|The Celebrity}}| chapter=5| passage=In the eyes of Mr. Farquhar Fenelon Cooke the apotheosis of the Celebrity was complete. The people of Asquith were not only willing to '''attend''' the house-warming, but had been worked up to the pitch of eagerness. The Celebrity as a matter of course was master of ceremonies.}}
#* '''1994''', {{w|Nelson Mandela}}, ''{{w|Long Walk to Freedom}}'', Abacus 2010, p. 20:
#*: I '''attended''' a one-room school next door to the palace and studied English, Xhosa, history and geography.
# {{lb|en|intransitive|legal}} To go to (a place) for some purpose (with {{m|en|at}}).
#* {{quote-web|en|author=Supreme Court of Canada|work=R. v. Côté|url=http://canlii.ca/t/fndv8|year=2011|accessdate=2016-05-08
|passage=Around 12:15 a.m. patrolling officers Tremblay and Mathieu '''attended''' at the appellant’s home.}}
#* {{quote-web|en|author=Prince Edward Island Court of Appeal| work=R. v. Yeo| url=http://canlii.ca/t/gnr68| year=2016| accessdate=2016-05-08| passage=There were a few errors in the testimony of [a civilian witness] which the trial judge noted – one, that they '''attended''' at the Fairhurst residence the day before the robbery, and two, that Wakelin was with them.}}
# To be present with; to accompany; to be united or consequent to.
#: {{ux|en|a measure '''attended''' with ill effects}}
#* '''1697''', {{w|John Dryden}}, ''The Georgics''
#*: What cares must then '''attend''' the toiling swain.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1922| author={{w|Ben Travers}}| chapter=5| title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1521052W A Cuckoo in the Nest]| passage=The most rapid and most seductive transition in all human nature is that which '''attends''' the palliation of a ravenous appetite. There is something humiliating about it.{{...}}Can those harmless but refined fellow-diners be the selfish cads whose gluttony and personal appearance so raised your contemptuous wrath on your arrival?}}
# To wait for; to await; to remain, abide, or be in store for.
#* {{RQ:Locke Human Understanding}}
#*: the different state of perfect happiness or misery that '''attends''' all men after this
#* {{RQ:Dryden The Indian Emperor}}
#*: Three days I promised to '''attend''' my doom.

